President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate two individuals to key positions in his Administration. The first nominee is David Carey Woll, Jr. from Connecticut, who is being nominated for the position of Assistant Secretary of Housing and Urban Development (Community Planning and Development). Mr. Woll is currently serving as the Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary of HUD's Office of Community Planning and Development, where he oversees funding for affordable housing, homelessness, and community revitalization initiatives. He also manages HUD's Community Development Block Grant Disaster Recovery program, which assists disaster-impacted communities. Mr. Woll has previous experience in various roles, including Deputy General Counsel for Enforcement and Fair Housing at HUD and Assistant United States Attorney. He holds an undergraduate degree from the University of Maryland and a Juris Doctor from the University of Virginia School of Law.

The second nominee is Alina L. Romanowski from Illinois, who is being nominated for the position of Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the State of Kuwait. Ms. Romanowski is a career member of the Senior Executive Service and currently serves as the Principal Deputy Coordinator for Counterterrorism at the Department of State. She has held various positions in the State Department, including Coordinator for United States Assistance to Europe and Eurasia and Deputy Assistant Secretary in the Bureau of Education and Cultural Affairs. She has also worked at the Defense Department as the founding Director of the Near East South Asia Center for Strategic Studies and as Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for Near Eastern and South Asian Affairs. Ms. Romanowski holds B.A. and M.A. degrees from the University of Chicago and has received several prestigious awards for her work. She is fluent in French and has studied Arabic and Hebrew.